<subSubSection pageId="93" pageNumber="94" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="93.[151,1437,150,465]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,222,248]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Kluge, Godunko &amp; Svitok" authorityYear="2020" box="[344,576,222,248]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Centroptella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pontica">
<emphasis box="[344,576,222,248]" italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Centroptella pontica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known as larvae only. Judging by hypodermal coloration of mature male larva, abdomen of male imago should have extensive reddish coloration on abdominal terga II–III and V–VI (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 414–418" captionStartId="91.[151,264,1838,1862]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,181,1814]" captionTargetId="figure-20@91.[170,1417,181,1814]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURES 414–418. Centroptella (Crassolus) pontica (photos by R. Godunko). 414–415, fore and hind legs of female larva, with subimaginal legs visible through larval cuticle; 416, fragment of larval cercus; 417, cuticle of larval abdominal terga; 418, male larva withy dark brown hypodermal coloration visible through cuticle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5577564" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5577564/files/figure.png" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Fig. 418</figureCitation>
). Judging by subimaginal legs visible through cuticle of mature female larva, tarsus of middle and hind legs has 1 apical spine on initial 3rd tarsomere (next after 1st+2nd tarsomere) (
<figureCitation box="[1001,1101,330,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 414–418" captionStartId="91.[151,264,1838,1862]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,181,1814]" captionTargetId="figure-20@91.[170,1417,181,1814]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURES 414–418. Centroptella (Crassolus) pontica (photos by R. Godunko). 414–415, fore and hind legs of female larva, with subimaginal legs visible through larval cuticle; 416, fragment of larval cercus; 417, cuticle of larval abdominal terga; 418, male larva withy dark brown hypodermal coloration visible through cuticle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5577564" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5577564/files/figure.png" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Fig. 415</figureCitation>
); in female—also with 1 apical spine (on tarsomere next after 2nd tarsomere (
<figureCitation box="[713,813,366,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 414–418" captionStartId="91.[151,264,1838,1862]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,181,1814]" captionTargetId="figure-20@91.[170,1417,181,1814]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURES 414–418. Centroptella (Crassolus) pontica (photos by R. Godunko). 414–415, fore and hind legs of female larva, with subimaginal legs visible through larval cuticle; 416, fragment of larval cercus; 417, cuticle of larval abdominal terga; 418, male larva withy dark brown hypodermal coloration visible through cuticle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5577564" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5577564/files/figure.png" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Fig. 414</figureCitation>
). A retained fragment of subimaginal gonostylus inside larval protogonostylus (
<figureCitation box="[419,517,402,428]" captionStart="FIGURES 419–420" captionStartId="92.[151,264,1925,1949]" captionTargetBox="[183,1405,616,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-166@92.[183,1405,616,1901]" captionTargetPageId="92" captionText="FIGURES 419–420. Centroptella (Crassolus) pontica. 419, larval metanotum with pair of bifurcate setae corresponding to f on Fig. 14 (SEM picture by R. Godunko); 420, fragment of male larval abdominal sternum IX with remnant of subimaginal gonostylus developing under larval cuticle (photo by P. Sroka). Abbreviations: gs1–gs3, segments of gonostyli; usg, unistyliger." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5577566" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5577566/files/figure.png" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Fig. 420</figureCitation>
) testifies that subimaginal gonostyli are folded in the « 
<taxonomicName box="[1141,1253,402,428]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Crassolus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1141,1253,402,428]" italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Crassolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- 
<typeStatus box="[1260,1311,403,429]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">type</typeStatus>
» pose [see 
<taxonomicName box="[151,263,438,464]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Crassolus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,263,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Crassolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(5)].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
